================================================================================
PLAN T020: DEBUGGABILITY BARRIERS & DIAGNOSTIC SOLUTIONS
================================================================================

This document identifies the top 3 biggest issues that make the desktop pet 
mascot application difficult to debug and profiles robust technical solutions for each.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. SILENT MAIN-PROCESS STEAMWORKS INITIALIZATION & NATIVE MODULE FAILURES (SELECTED & IMPLEMENTED)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

* The Barrier:
  The Electron main process (`main.js`) handles native Steamworks API binding. If 
  loading fails due to mismatched DLLs, missing prebuild binaries, or Steam being 
  offline, these exceptions are swallowed or printed only to system terminal stdout. 
  Because they occur in the main process, they are invisible in the renderer's 
  Chromium DevTools console. Developers see "achievements not unlocking" without 
  any visual error stack.

* Proposed Solution: Unified Diagnostic Logging & IPC Trace Stream
  - Implement a central diagnostic logger in [main.js](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/main.js) 
    that writes both initialization success/failure messages and exception stacks 
    to a persistent `diagnostics.log` file in the user's `assets/` folder.
  - Expose a `get-diagnostic-logs` IPC listener so the renderer can fetch these 
    system logs.
  - Render a collapsible "Diagnostics Console" inside the Settings Panel in 
    [renderer.js](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/renderer.js) 
    showing real-time status of Steamworks connection, loaded modules, and file writes.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. TRANSPARENT CLICK-THROUGH HOVER LOCK-OUTS (SELECTED & IMPLEMENTED)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

* The Barrier:
  When click-through ignore-mouse events (`setIgnoreMouseEvents(true, { forward: true })`) 
  are active, clicks are forwarded straight to background OS windows. If a bug 
  locks the window in hover click-through state, the developer cannot right-click to 
  inspect, click the settings cog, or focus the window to trigger DevTools keyboard 
  shortcuts. Devs are locked out of their own application interface and must force-kill 
  the process.

* Proposed Solution: Developer Mode CLI Flag & Visual Boundary Grid
  - Introduce a `--dev` or `--no-click-through` command line switch checked on startup 
    in [main.js](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/main.js):
    ```javascript
    const isDevMode = process.argv.includes('--dev');
    ```
  - If in developer mode, permanently disable click-through behavior (bypass 
    `setIgnoreMouseEvents`) and pass an indicator to the renderer.
  - In [style.css](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/style.css), 
    add a developer layout class that renders a subtle semi-transparent border 
    and grid around the canvas when developer mode is active so that the physical 
    window bounds are clearly visible.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. SILENT CONFIGURATION RESET EVENTS (SELECTED & IMPLEMENTED)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

* The Barrier:
  The application implements a robust self-healing fallback loop when parsing corrupted 
  or empty configuration files. If reading fails, it resets configuration variables to 
  factory defaults in memory and overwrites the config file. While this prevents crashes, 
  it does so silently. Developers cannot easily tell if the app successfully loaded their 
  saved custom window parameters or silently reset due to a parser failure, causing 
  mysterious "lost settings" bugs.

* Proposed Solution: Diagnostic Recovery Flags & In-App Toast Alerts
  - Modify the recovery path in `readSettingsFile()` inside [renderer.js](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/renderer.js): 
    when recovery defaults are applied, set an active recovery flag (`wasConfigHealed = true`).
  - Upon initialization completion, check `wasConfigHealed`. If true, trigger a visible, 
    persistent diagnostic notification toast (`⚠️ Configuration Corrupted: Reset to Default Values`) 
    so the developer is immediately aware that config recovery occurred.
  - Write a corresponding `[Config Recovery]` entry into the `diagnostics.log` file.
